document.title: Maryland Early Learning Standards Birth – 8 Years

382D92E2C7144F5CA4146B7A39F1B981.description:
Begins to
understand
explanations of
events that have not
been experienced
directly, as long as
the child has had
similar experience.

72CC46420A5F47BD96864BAB40717DCD.description:
Increased ability
to understand explanations when
concrete objects and
actions support the
verbal explanation,
and phenomena are
directly observable
(e.g., "When we mix
colors, we get a new
color. See what
color you get when
you mix yellow with
blue").

9BF9A58919AD446C83F763D7C8945AF1.description:
Becomes more
animated in play
(e.g., using different
voices for the baby,
dog, etc.)

0AEFACD8C9E746FF9C8870B3A42A5DFB.description:
Uses objects as
symbolic props (e.g.,
places a shell on top
of a dollhouse and
declares it to be a
satellite dish).

3DEE9AF265CC46F1AB3596B6D91A906B.description:
Communicates
thoughts and
feelings through role
play though may still
need adult support
(e.g., play acts being
a kitten seeking
affection and hugs).

48CDC23964E74A93BA239D11AC34268B.description:
Engages in
Pretend Play and
Acts Out Roles

F81669BAADE842D3A65EFEEE27D2B206.description:
Uses art to reflect
thoughts and
feelings (e.g.,
transforms a list of
favorite foods that
his teacher had
recorded on paper into a mobile from
which illustrations
of these foods are
hung).

2E81ED2D0ACD43A9BEA19CADFBE9C2C3.description:
Begins to create
art that is more
realistic and includes
some details of
objects, animals or
people.
Such details are
typically
remembered
features that have
made an impression,
but do not include
all that is seen or
known (e.g., draws a
picture of a car with
four wheels but no
windows).

F87729A361B249FD872C49ECB8FCD19F.description:
Represents
People, Places, or
Things Through
Drawings,
Movement, and
Three Dimension
Objects

032F101736FE43D1B18F7F49CE3E2591.description:
Begins identifying
when things are not put away in designated areas.

751A830DA35E4A3D928CC9D08624C868.description:
Recognizes and is
responsible for
returning items to
appropriate location
with prompting.

E3CC37A7CF1A44B2932D6F80B2F305EE.description:
Begins to
demonstrate
appropriate use of
classroom materials
with modeling (e.g.,
using glue in an art
project appropriately
or turning book
pages with care).

24F11BB5CCF24A4794DFB999EAE2D510.description:
Helps with clean
up after activities
with prompting.

E02CEF334B44414A9173FC58C8AFFBF1.description:
Demonstrates
Appropriate Use of Materials or
Belongings and
Those of Others

DF2A86C533F4451F97A5A3B6FCE9EE06.description:
Engages in out of
the classroom
activities
(i.e., recess) and
successfully reenters classroom
without disruption.

2EBB524A9EB34F748ED485FC0F027269.description:
Frequently
demonstrates
comfort with the
transition from
home to the
classroom
environment (e.g.,
easily calms down
when parents leave).

22A11AC1E3994645AAB71F268198BC72.description:
Manages
separation anxiety
from home to
school by kissing
caregiver goodbye
or waving from the
window every day.

EA40A2802F09458A968D548306CA036A.description:
Demonstrates the
Ability to Adopt to
New Environments with Appropriate
Behaviors with
Adult Support

CAC9C8A4BADB4352874C1221FFACA78B.description:
Occasionally
demonstrates the
ability to stop an
engaging activity to
help clean up with
and requiring less
support and
guidance from an
adult.

8EEF4F4632644E938393807BAE7316F3.description:
Takes and gives
cues to other
children during
transition and
models their
appropriate behavior
with adult support.

9233AFC6C2FA4B038E4C2361D8EC1B01.description:
Demonstrates the
Ability to Postpone
Activity and Start
Another

41B130622C0A4E8C96CDBCE8419AE07A.description: Understanding & complying with classroom rules, routines, and expectations.

6FBA8EB380404B3389264B7B787F684D.description: Requires fewer prompts to follow classroom routines and is able to independently anticipate what happens next.

6E6C77E91E83474CA6A1CE1E1B7F9E63.description:
Behaves
appropriately within
the context of the
classroom routines
with adult modeling
and support (i.e.
listens when someone else is talking or raises hand to share).

668BFF99A70244609531C35B0FDED01E.description:
Takes initiative
with assigned or
chosen tasks relating
to classroom
routines.

8675CD8C79A54937ADEA257C1004DA4D.description:
Responds to
teacher directions or
signals consistently.

B536AB7217A3402B90A77B86A29C1E82.description: Understanding & complying with classroom rules, routines, & expectations.

156E6DA46BC1458688A25C9474EC1CE9.description:
Suggests solutions
to problems with
other children, while
continuing to seek
adults' help (e.g.,
says, "Hey,
Benjamin! We can BOTH be firemen!").

ED350B935BDF4BF087326375B3CCED88.description:
Begins to try to
please other children
(e.g., says, "You can
come to my birthday
party, ok?").

9DD2D56A01F744128692F85C277C3819.description:
Shows further
progress in
developing
friendships with
peers, even if a bond
is formed with just
one other child.

CE6DB63485B641BA86BDA60F0F2B9BD2.description:
Responds more
appropriately and
sympathetically to
peers who are in
need, upset, hurt, or
angry (e.g., says,
"Don't cry, Willy.
My daddy can fix
that bike. He knows
how").

E4BAC5B569414E88AD09D86583F8BB4C.description:
Will often notice
that a problem can
be resolved by a
change in approach
(e.g., trying to fit a
puzzle piece a few
times and then
rotating to find a
better fit).

54BC044D9E8541CDAC45971C1B604EE3.description:
Experiences
difficulty with
drawing, cutting,
and writing, but
persists with adult
support and
encouragement until
task is complete.

ED764BF4613043F392C0302A996EDA79.description:
Continues to
attempt to build a
tower even after
three or more
unsuccessful
attempts with adult
support and
encouragement.

A20B51F6ED3E42F59DFACB40DBE51734.description:
Persists in the
Face of Failure

A65342BC0E15429BBE65BEF7ECFD27F7.description:
Will often persist
in working to
complete all aspects
of a planned task
(e.g., when building
a zoo in the block
area, will keep
working until every
animal has a cage).

3215CE7F25E14833B6F33B220A1AC2EE.description:
Keeps working to
complete a task even
if it is moderately
difficult (e.g.,
persists with a
somewhat
challenging wooden
puzzle).

699BCAC668DC4D19B36A9BA79D7BD397.description:
Persists with a
wider variety of
tasks, activities, and
experiences with
adult prompting.

6CD94B0412734075AA0EDA87D9FD8D48.description:
Persists in an
Activity From Start
to Finish (Complete
a Task)--
Independently

B01F741EB8664267AB1CA4D65B3D384D.description:
Develops greater
ability to set goals
and follow a plan
(e.g., child says, "I'm
going to pick up all
these branches," and
then works until it is
done).

003361B0642742349E076188820C7664.description:
Further expands
areas of decisionmaking (e.g., child
may say, "This
morning I'm going
to work on my Lego
building").

E1B41D3209C5443FBE268FFC20D7048D.description:
Shows interest in
leading activities and
taking responsibility
during cleanup
activities.

C9F1D683F3644B638FF5723CFF48E73F.description:
When prompted,
initiates plan of
activities.

5ABE1E572671477F938565F8E61ABAF5.description:
Independence in
Learning—Plans
and Initiates
Projects

96975A191193402D97AEAA5223B35897.description:
Seeks new and
varied experiences
and challenges (e.g.,
puts materials
together in new
ways to test results;
joins in a peercreated game or
activity, tries to
dress a new doll or
builds a new
construction toy).

050DBA77F6204F12B4C00ED7B79B3A68.description:
Starts to show an
increase in
enthusiasm for
learning letters,
shapes, and
numbers (e.g., while
looking at a book
with dad, points to a
word that contains
the letter "S" and
says, "S! That's in my name! What is
that word?").

4E6685A421B64735B12AA9692596423B.description:
Asks questions
about future events,
as well as about the
here and now (e.g.,
asks "When will we
go to Sarah's house
again?").

C25B94A002494B418BA13C0194260AC0.description:
Asks to
participate in new
experiences that he
or she has observed
or has heard of
others participating
in (e.g., says, "Janice
goes fishing. Can
I?").

6F386F8359254B32955E4EB13045F312.description:
Elaborates on
experiments by
attempting to
replicate results
using different
materials (e.g.,
gathers several
materials to drop in
the water table, then sorts what sinks vs.
what floats).

603FA8B0EB8143FF94D4DC3DADF606CE.description:
Poses questions
to seek explanations
about topics of
interest with adult
support and
modeling.

337D2385DF8B47F78DFB1625D25F9018.description:
Asks questions
about future events,
as well as about the
here and now (e.g.,
asks, "When will we
go to Val’s?).

FB68765FBAC741309CDF9123F0D6127A.description:
Desire to
Learn—Ask
Questions and Seeks
New Information

E40FC13ABD38414CACDA49F92345859D.description:
When faced with
a problem, can be
reminded to slow
down and think
about what to do.

DFC53F92ACCE4195BE3BCFF1B9EAF47B.description:
When in conflict
with another child,
increasingly able to
suggest possible
solutions.

4F9BC4FC3C6D49588D3CF4D984F438E6.description:
Continues to
become more
cognitively flexible
and is able to draw
on varied resources
to solve problems
(e.g., tries to build a
large structure with
blocks, but the
building keeps
falling down. After
several failed
attempts, he or she
tries making a larger
base. May also look
at how other
children have made
their buildings).

B811BF10A6DD47C7A2B5822B848BDB24.description:
Begins to employ
their own solutions
to problems through
trial and error (e.g.,
tries different pegs
to see which one
fits).

88CAE8E7511D4747AAAA6C2C351509CD.description:
Flexible Problem
Solving - Seeks
Multiple Solutions
to a Question, Task,
or Problem

6AAF1AB11F7A4C38A226E641A377DEEA.description:
Able to change
the categories used
for sorting materials
with help (e.g., sort
by color then by
shape).

1A0A6F585D8E46C5B1A582D49A0EC0FF.description:
Will often
recognize and
correct mistakes
independently.

88373548A55C42BC8E3A6210460AEECE.description:
Can follow
different rules in
different familiar contexts with
minimal reminders
(e.g., take off shoes
at home but not at
school).

C24AE3B658F74B92879701475CE8CABC.description:
Can enjoy games
like Simon Says that
require child to
follow two different
rules when cued
(copying, not
copying).

21AE4266E8F446C2A52643ED65AD0E74.description:
Can switch roles
in dramatic play.

22CF4845C2E24323802419C391821AEE.description:
Can
independently
sustain a character in
pretend play for ten
minutes or longer.

77B9FD55A8AA4962A06E9ABF7BD959ED.description:
Can Flexibly
Apply Rules to
Games and
Behavior

DC320E207C514FD49602593699AFA0E7.description:
Can enjoy more
complex memory
games with more
cards or objects.

71F0C56C35184FDDA9DF2BBDFC49FDF6.description:
Can keep track of
a few different
objects for short
periods of time.

9E5CF7921DD2434AA956C7A7779CAE5F.description:
Can hold in mind
the comments of
peers and respond
appropriately during
a short class
discussion.

C2C11C365A564F149B931E9F56755652.description:
Can remember
and follow two-step
directions without
prompting.

C58C6E14B6CE4A55A5DAF35F71BB890D.description:
Can remember
and follow multiple
classroom rules with
visual and auditory
cues.

E9028A2FC4184287818D5CF7E5F207AD.description:
Will frequently
consider a couple of
possibilities before
making a choice.

0D24694906E145168E51B1C5B97EAE36.description:
Can remember
recent events in a
story and use this
information to
shape predictions
and questions.

B56A580A2CF44C738A73E41CBD885076.description:
Demonstrate the
Ability to Hold and
Manipulate
Information

57F76A78D4644D8B815B8DD157487748.description:
May need a
reminder to return
to an earlier task
after an interruption.

D141869920CB4BF9993D956DB002178F.description:
Remains on task
during an activity set
by the teacher for
short periods of
time despite
distractions with
minimal prompting
from adults (e.g.,
can ignore other
activities nearby and
hold focus on a
teacher directed
small group activity).

B7579BDD98EB4A35AA5B1599A22073E0.description:
Attentiveness—
Resists Distraction
to Maintain Focus
on Tasks Set By
Someone Else

AA625D0BD28949AEBA6202657204BF45.description:
Capable of
sustaining focus on
longer-term or
complex projects,
with support from
an adult.

BA404F85A4964BAAAC444D3C1439D150.description: Increases ability to ignore distractions and sustain attention on topics that are of interest to the child (e.g., can focus on a drawing even when other children are nearby; might say, “I’ll play with you later. I want to finish this”).

2CDC848F698A4530A48DA0A3A51E57DC.description: Attentiveness— Resists Distraction to Maintain Focus on Tasks of Interest to the Child

3B419C9DFF91470D8FD100D62ABFEE9E.description:
Learns coping
strategies (e.g., using
words, pretend play,
drawing) to establish
greater control and
competence in
managing intense
emotions (e.g., after
going to the
emergency room, he
or she may
repeatedly play out
the experience with
dolls and stuffed
animals) and resist
impulse to harm
self, others or
property.

BFBE509FFD9B4BCC84540128CA214973.description:
Refrains from
Emotional
Outbursts and
Unsafe Behaviors

D841AED98A4041E9A92D66DE5E36CEF5.description:
Can wait for a
highly desired food
or object, although may occasionally
need reminders.

345DA4B95F46459DB8BEBCA0A6BB2A91.description:
Able to take turns
with preferred toys
or classroom
materials (i.e., waits
for an object
without grabbing
with minimal
prompting).

786848C571E84A58900FE04425C7977A.description:
Independently
waits for an object
without grabbing
most of the time.

E96C62B4F2284C219A2496A66DF561D7.description:
Able to play
games like Red
Light, Green light
that require waiting
for signal to do
something with
adult support.

359892EAE27647D68FBB9F04C2218256.description:
Sometimes able to
resist habits when
they are no longer appropriate (e.g.,
may remember
while walking to the
bathroom that the
paper towels have
moved and change
course).

581AC956FED947C3BC2875642A127117.description:
Can play the role
of a teacher in game
and monitor other
children’s behavior
and remind them to
follow the rules.

D0B7D2D6D21943ADB31D9E37C01E00D8.description:
Can more reliably
control impulses
during structured
activities that are
familiar (e.g., raising
hand to talk).

66C83E928116453596F28ABD87FD7842.description:
Avoids imitating
the negative
behavior of peers
with minimal
prompting from
adults.

CAAA7760DA1A4FD88AB5DAF5C0FFC970.description:
Has an awareness of conflict resolution strategies
but is not able to
independently
implement
consistently (e.g.,
understands a story
when a social
strategy was used
but can’t adapt
functionally).

F9CB025FDADC43878D73A9D0AE13F398.description: Discusses possible solutions with peers with adult assistance.

BBF178AD5E484252ACA7D69EA263F35F.description: Seeks adult help when solving inter- personal conflicts.

7D2A818E831A442AB621AB4E7597E71A.description:
Identifies interpersonal conflicts
and begins to
manage emotions
more effectively
using self-talk with
adult support and
modeling (e.g.,
“Take three deep
breaths, and then
ask Caleb for another turn”).

D7B9F9F8156D4D8A8C3CA2168D1F3E2A.description:
Identifies and
negotiates when a
peer is not given the
same instructions or
structure (e.g.,
“William’s mommy
lets him watch Dora.
Why can’t I?”).

368668FD53A64BE3A4A6C22571DBB65B.description:
Identifies
differences or
similarities between
self as compared to
others (e.g., children
with disability,
gender, hair color,
etc.).

68E671E836EE4BF8822ECE03CEFE5334.description:
Recognizes
Differences or
Similarities Between
Self as Compared to others.

B10D00A3DECE450B850CC2891F46283D.description:
Shares materials
and equipment with
other children with
adult modeling and
support.

3AF010BE61A04FF486D2C86E0D2D2BCB.description:
Has one or more
special friendships.

DDC42ABA542A4ACAA2C91B4DA288EA21.description:
Plays or Works
with Others
Cooperatively

60102706C16A4706B0AFEBF5525AE4B8.description:
Shows concern
for peers who are
upset or hurt.

DE70F6CFB37F49399ABBF3C567B3B7EF.description:
Seeks adult
assistance for
classmates who need support.

ECBDDC61939E4E9C85968D0342F07A17.description:
Understands
wider array of
feelings (e.g.,
frustrated, scared,
lonely) and
expresses them to
others.

F33AD5EC1E614996A0FB8938B6768CFB.description:
Communicates
negative and
positive emotions
verbally and
responds to teacher
prompts or
directions.

CFD94F592C7341758B4759E716FE0568.description:
Expresses,
Understands, and
Responds to
Feelings/Emotions
of Others

EBB1028E9EC24B7B98606920012B453C.description:
Further expands
areas of decision
making (e.g., child
may say, "This
morning I'm going
to work on my Lego
building").

D72CFB6284154B22BE064EAB66F0E591.description:
Begins identifying
when things are not
put away in
designated areas.

CCF6D502BB36421ABA7970C8F52BE8DA.description:
Shows interest in
leading activities and
taking responsibility
during cleanup
activities.

B5CD2B84CBA84A22B86898E27B3029BB.description:
Requires fewer
prompts to follow
classroom routines
and is able to
independently
anticipate what
happens next.

8673FED2E1C841C4A2174B60E6761117.description:
Seeks new and
varied experiences
and challenges (i.e.,
put materials
together in new
ways to test results;
joins in a peer
created game or
activity).

2192BE9E03BF4F3E80860763FFAADE03.description:
Demonstrates
Independence inD
range of Routines
and Tasks
